{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583111"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:07:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:07:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2005"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.54,0.34,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51693"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2005"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36995"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5012"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51693"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with chest pain. He is diagnosed with an acute coronary syndrome and requires antiplatelet therapy. The cardiologist is considering various antiplatelet medications, including those that act on the P2Y12 receptor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antiplatelet medications reversibly binds to the P2Y12 receptor?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Clopidogrel","Ticagrelor","Prasugrel","Dipyridamole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETicagrelor\u003C/strong\u003E is the only P2Y12 receptor inhibitor that binds reversibly to the receptor. This property distinguishes it from other P2Y12 inhibitors and can be advantageous in certain clinical scenarios, such as when rapid offset of action is desired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprasugrel\u003C/strong\u003E are also P2Y12 receptor inhibitors, but they bind irreversibly to the receptor. These medications require metabolic activation to produce their active metabolites, which then irreversibly inhibit platelet function for the lifespan of the platelet (about 7-10 days).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E works through a different mechanism. It is an irreversible cyclo-oxygenase I (COX-1) inhibitor. By inhibiting COX-1, aspirin prevents the formation of thromboxane A2, a potent platelet activator and vasoconstrictor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDipyridamole\u003C/strong\u003E has a unique mechanism of action among these options. It inhibits phosphodiesterase and therefore inhibits endogenous adenosine reuptake by increasing platelet cyclic AMP (cAMP). This results in coronary vasodilation and inhibition of platelet aggregation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the mechanisms of action of these antiplatelet medications is crucial for their appropriate use in various clinical scenarios. The reversible binding of ticagrelor to the P2Y12 receptor allows for more rapid offset of its antiplatelet effect compared to clopidogrel and prasugrel, which can be beneficial in patients who may require urgent surgery or have a high bleeding risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["P2Y12 receptor inhibitors include clopidogrel, ticagrelor, and prasugrel.","Ticagrelor is the only P2Y12 receptor inhibitor that binds reversibly to the receptor.","Aspirin is an irreversible cyclo-oxygenase I inhibitor, while dipyridamole inhibits phosphodiesterase."],"references":["Antiplatelet drugs. In: Australian Medicines Handbook [online]. 2020; cited 2020 Apr 23. Available at: https://amhonline.amh.net.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2005"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T10:53:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T10:53:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2005"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51693"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":